{
  "chapter_number": 12,
  "chapter_title": "Storage Classes in C",
  "sections": [
    {
      "section_title": "Introduction",
      "keywords": ["storage classes"],
      "content": "Storage classes define the scope, visibility, lifetime, and storage location of variables."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "What is a Storage Class?",
      "keywords": ["definition"],
      "content": "A storage class determines how and where variables are stored and accessed in a program."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Types of Storage Classes",
      "keywords": ["types"],
      "content": [
        "auto",
        "register",
        "static",
        "extern"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "auto Storage Class",
      "keywords": ["auto"],
      "content": "auto is the default storage class for local variables."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Features of auto",
      "keywords": ["auto features"],
      "content": [
        "Default local variable",
        "Stored in memory",
        "Scope limited to block",
        "Destroyed after block execution"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "register Storage Class",
      "keywords": ["register"],
      "content": "register requests the compiler to store variables in CPU registers for faster access."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Features of register",
      "keywords": ["register features"],
      "content": [
        "Fast access",
        "Stored in CPU register if available",
        "Cannot use address operator easily"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "static Storage Class",
      "keywords": ["static"],
      "content": "A static variable retains its value throughout program execution."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Features of static",
      "keywords": ["static features"],
      "content": [
        "Retains value between function calls",
        "Initialized only once",
        "Lifetime throughout program execution"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "extern Storage Class",
      "keywords": ["extern"],
      "content": "extern is used to access global variables declared in another file."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Features of extern",
      "keywords": ["extern features"],
      "content": [
        "Accesses external variables",
        "Supports multiple file programs",
        "Shares global data"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Scope of Variables",
      "keywords": ["scope"],
      "content": [
        "Local Scope",
        "Global Scope"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Lifetime of Variables",
      "keywords": ["lifetime"],
      "content": "Lifetime refers to how long a variable remains in memory during program execution."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Comparison of Storage Classes",
      "keywords": ["comparison"],
      "content": [
        "auto: Temporary local variable",
        "register: Faster local variable",
        "static: Retains value",
        "extern: Access external global variable"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Example Program",
      "keywords": ["example"],
      "content": "#include <stdio.h>\n\nvoid demo()\n{\n static int count=0;\n count++;\n printf(\"%d\\n\",count);\n}\n\nint main()\n{\n demo();\n demo();\n demo();\n return 0;\n}"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Applications",
      "keywords": ["applications"],
      "content": [
        "Memory management",
        "Large software systems",
        "Performance optimization",
        "Global data sharing"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "summary": [
    "Storage classes define scope and lifetime.",
    "auto is the default storage class.",
    "register provides faster access.",
    "static retains values between function calls.",
    "extern allows access to global variables across files."
  ]
}
